Data Description:¶

A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service").

Dataset:¶

The dataset has the following columns:

  • tweet_id
  • airline_sentiment
  • airline_sentiment_confidence
  • negativereason
  • negativereason_confidence
  • airline
  • airline_sentiment_gold
  • name
  • negativereason_gold
  • retweet_count
  • text
  • tweet_coord
  • tweet_created
  • tweet_location
  • user_timezone

Objective:¶

To implement the techniques learned as a part of the course.

View & Opinion¶

  • When looking into a sentiments analysis problem we need to make sure that all the data pre-processing doesnt affect the meaning of the sentence and we can accurately identify the sentiment trying to be convied .
  • Using sentiments analysis companies can learn how to improve and effectively implement strategies so as to increase customer base ans ensure returning customers

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def perc_on_bar(z):

    total = len(data1[z]) # length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    ax = sns.countplot(data1[z],palette='Paired')
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percantage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

Lemmetization

In [34]:
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer() # asigning the word net lemmatizer as the lemmatizer 

def remove_non_ascii(words): #Removing non-ASCII characters from list of tokenized words
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = unicodedata.normalize('NFKD', word).encode('ascii', 'ignore').decode('utf-8', 'ignore')
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def to_lowercase(words): #Converting all characters to lowercase from list of tokenized words
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = word.lower()
        new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_punctuation(words): #Removing punctuation from list of tokenized words
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        new_word = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', word)
        if new_word != '':
            new_words.append(new_word)
    return new_words

def remove_stopwords(words): #Removing stop words from list of tokenized words
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
        if word not in stopwords:
            new_words.append(word)
    return new_words

def lemmatize_list(words): # Lemmatizing the words 
    new_words = []
    for word in words:
      new_words.append(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word, pos='v'))
    return new_words

def normalize(words): # normalizing the words 
    words = remove_non_ascii(words)
    words = to_lowercase(words)
    words = remove_punctuation(words)
    words = remove_stopwords(words)
    words = lemmatize_list(words)
    return ' '.join(words)

data1['text'] = data1.apply(lambda row: normalize(row['text']), axis=1)
data1.head() # printing the first 5 values of the dataset

In [44]:
modelname =['Decision Tree','Random Forest','Bagging']
In [45]:
model_name=[]
technique_type=[]
train_score=[]
test_score=[]
cv_min=[]
cv_max=[]
cv_av=[]
cv_std=[]
std_score=[]

i=0
for m in models:
    
    m.fit(x_train, y_train)
    
    print(modelname[i])
    
    model_name.append(modelname[i])
    i+=1
    
    train_score.append(m.score(x_train,y_train))
    test_score.append(m.score(x_test,y_test))
    
    sf=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, random_state=20, shuffle=True)
    kf=cross_val_score(m, x_train, y_train, cv=sf)
    
    cv_min.append(np.min(kf))
    cv_max.append(np.max(kf))
    cv_av.append(np.mean(kf))
    cv_std.append(np.std(kf))
    technique_type.append('Count Vectorize')

In [55]:
models=[model_dt, model_rf, model_bg]
modelname=['Decision Tree','Random Forest','Bagging']
In [56]:
model_name=[]
train_score=[]
test_score=[]
cv_min=[]
cv_max=[]
cv_av=[]
cv_std=[]
std_score=[]

i=0
for m in models:
    
    m.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    print(modelname[i])
    
    model_name.append(modelname[i])
    i+=1
    
    train_score.append(m.score(X_train,y_train))
    test_score.append(m.score(X_test,y_test))
    
    sf=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, random_state=20, shuffle=True)
    kf=cross_val_score(m, X_train, y_train, cv=sf)
    
    
    
    cv_min.append(np.min(kf))
    cv_max.append(np.max(kf))
    cv_av.append(np.mean(kf))
    cv_std.append(np.std(kf))

Summary¶

  • We worked a dataset based on the sentiments of various problems in different US airlines .
  • We looked into barplots for the various airlines and in what percentage they were appearing the dataset, sentiments and their percentages, and the negative reasons and their percentages
  • We looked into the data and did various Pre-Processing techniques before feeding the data into the model i.e removing HTML tags,stopwords, removing accented characters , Tokenization etc.
  • We used 2 vectorizers CountVectorizer and Tf-idf Vectorizer
  • We build 3 models Decission Tree ,Random Forest and Bagging classifiers for both of the vectorizers
  • We evaluated all the models and Random Forest on both of the vectorizers performed the best
  • Random Forest with CountVectorizer is the suggested model as it gave a 76.95% on the test set and accurately classified 3380 sentiments out of 4392 total values .
  • Thank,greatness,jetblue,usairways and flight were the top features for the model
